<h5 class="subheading">Introduction</h5>





<p>
Today, consumers rarely check out at a business without a cashier asking for their personal information. Systems that were once made of punchcards and collectible items to trade-in for a freebie have turned into very sophisticated apps and points systems tracking purchases and money spent. These systems have allowed companies to diversify and weigh the rewards they give their shoppers; for example, Harris Teeter has found a way to systemically track what you are buying using your VIC card and offer you coupons for certain items based on past purchases. This information might have only been used to send shoppers promotional coupons and store catalogs in the past, but companies can now use this information to track what people are buying and encourage shoppers to buy more things and spend more money. While gamifying the consumer experience is marketed as a way to make shopping more fun and cost-effective, it comes with harmful side effects to the shopper such as overconsumption and overspending.
</p>

<p>
In order to explore the gamification of the consumer experience, it is important to understand how gamification has come to exist in the retail industry. Gamification is defined as “any process that makes use of games or gameful elements to achieve instrumental goals.” This definition is broad, and it is meant to be; to “gamify” is to create “any solution that employs games or ideas/elements from games to solve instrumental needs or problems” (Tondello). The term “gamification” dates back to the digital media industry in 2008. While “gamification” was used to describe the “increasing adoption, institutionalization and ubiquity of (video) games in everyday life,” the term also came to represent a second notion that since video games are entertaining and successful in garnering intense and long-time user engagement, game elements should also be able to make ”other, non-game products and services more enjoyable and engaging as well” (Deterding 9,10). In the consumer market, this meant that businesses began using games to make more profit.
</p>

<p>
Kai Huotari and Juho Hamari consider games systems, noting that games, like systems, are “composed of several interacting sets of mechanisms and actors” and always require “the active involvement of at least one player” (Huotari 22). Huotari and Hamari assert that not all games are inherently successful, and that “gamification can only attempt to support the user in creating gameful experiences that promote the user’s overall value creation” (Huotari 26). Although companies “produce” the game in relation to their own business, consumers are “co-producers” by the fact that a game’s success relies on their interest and engagement. Not everyone likes to play every game, and because the gamification of the consumer experience depends on consumer buy-in, games are developed in an attempt to support, embellish, or enhance the consumer experience using rules, goal-setting, variable outcomes, feedback, and rewards, rather than promote the development of a consumer experience (Huotari 26).
</p>

<p>
Within the gamified experience, researchers from the Labovitz School of Business & Economics at the University of Minnesota Duluth have identified four key experiences a consumer can have; as observers, spectators, apprentices, or performers (McCarthy). The researchers likened the gamified experience to a boxing match; in a boxing match, one can observe by watching from their TVs at home, physically be at the arena and watch the match as a spectator, become a performer by boxing in the match, or become an apprentice and training in hopes of one day becoming a boxer. These four roles can intersect to create different player experiences. For example, when a player is actively absorbed by an experience such as attending a college lecture, the player is an apprentice. When the player passively absorbs an experience, such as watching a movie, they are the observer. When a player passively immerses themselves in an experience like going on a scenic drive they are a spectator. When the player is actively immersed in an experience like playing a sport, the player is a performer with “a measure of control as to how the experience unfolds” (McCarthy 354).
</p>

<p>
Today, it is easy to label the practice of gamification as “bullshit,” but gamification science still remains “a distinct subdiscipline of game science consisting of researchers adopting a social scientific epistemological footing” (Landers et al.). Game developers have learned to better integrate game elements to real-world processes, and in order to do so have also gained a better understanding of how consumers’ brains work. Many modern programs that gamify the shopping experience emphasize tangible rewards such as points, badges, and leaderboards. By emphasizing tangible rewards, these programs encourage extrinsic motivation, which refers to “doing something because it leads to a separable outcome,” for example being motivated to buy something because of the points or other rewards that come with buying it (Dahlstrøm). By encouraging a player’s extrisitc motivation, these games harm a player’s intrinsic motivation, or desire to pursue an activity simply because it is “inherently interesting or enjoyable.” Why go shopping because one enjoys it when one needs to go shopping in order to derive joy from the points they will acquire from buying something?
</p>




