<p>
Customers used to have to enter a retailer’s space (visit them in-store or online) in order to actively participate in the shopping experience, but a rise in mobile devices and mobile marketing allows retailers to invert the experience and enter the customer’s personal environment instead by paying for digital ad space on social media platforms and other digital public domains (Hofacker). Unlike traditional marketing, mobile marketing utilizes time to add complexity via real-time engagement, such as sending time-sensitive communications encouraging shoppers to act by a certain time or sending marketing messages at a time of day known for high-interactivity (Krief). Because the world is so digital, companies know that consumers are seeing their messages instantaneously; as a result, consumers are constantly and consistently bombarded with marketing messages 24/7. These marketing tactics bleed into the games that companies develop to further engage shoppers.
</p>

<p>
Because targeting a consumer’s extrinsic motivation has is such a successful marketing tactic, many companies have developed programs that do so, ranging from loyalty apps that give customers points for purchases such as Dunkin’ Donuts to airlines offering points for every mile flown with their specific airline. Oftentimes, these games will encourage brand loyalty by allowing customers to “spend” their points on more of that company’s product—in the case of Dunkin’ Donuts, coffee or food items and, in the case of airlines, seat upgrades and money off of future flights. By encouraging customers to engage in a cycle of spending money, earning points, spending points, and then spending more money in order to earn more points to spend, companies have created a learned pattern that traps customers into perpetually spending money on their goods and services. By encouraging consumers to “win” a game with no ending, businesses know that if they can convince consumers to buy in to their games with enticing enough deals their customer base will continue to grow. Higher stakes services such as credit cards have also gamified and implemented their own rewards programs.
</p>

<p>
In his article Developing a Theory of Gamified Learning: Linking Serious Games and Gamification of Learning, Richard Landers discusses the fact that “gamification is intended to influence a learning-related behavior or attitude” (Landers 763). Encouraging customers to consume high-stakes services for rewards such as lines of credit could have potentially negative consequences for customers who do not have the initial means with which to buy into the system or the knowledge or willpower to keep the game from running away from them. After a company has successfully gotten a customer to buy into their loyalty program, what happens if a customer is unable to dig themselves out of the debt they have assumed in order to gain a credit card’s rewards? High-end and luxury brands are far less likely to use games as a way to entice customers to buy their services because their scarcity, luxury status, and brand association is enough to draw customers. If only low-end brands and companies that make money off of their customers’ lack of money utilize games as a part of the consumer experience, it is because these companies recognize their customers’ lack of desire to spend money and are using games in order to coerce them into spending money they don’t want to spend or, worse, don’t have to begin with.
</p>

<p>
In their paper The Ethics of Gamification in a Marketing Context, Andrea Stevenson Thorpe acknowledges how stealthily persuasive business practices work at a cognitive level to persuade customers to buy into gamified shopping experiences as well as “ethical implications” this “potential deception” has on consumers (Thorpe 597). Consumer experiences that are low-rewarding and unenjoyable unless a customer actively participates aren’t fun for shoppers. Furthermore, modern mobile marketing is nowhere near as effective as it can be from a business standpoint despite massive efforts of businesses to market and encourage consumption (Hofacker). By ensuring customers are participating in gamified experiences that are high-reward and fun no matter whether shoppers purchase anything, companies will not only improve the customer experience but encourage higher customer retention rates and garner more business in the process. Thorpe suggests businesses abide by the ‘golden rule’ and ‘disclosure rule’ in order to provide consumers with a better gamified experience; by encouraging game designers to imagine how they would feel if they were the user instead of the designer, game designers will be encouraged to design gamified shopping expereinces with the player’s best interest in mind rather than a company’s profit. Scott Nicholson supports Thorpe’s assertion by also stating that “result from the positive and meaningful benefits for the user” (Nicholson 5). One way to help make user benefits positive and meaningful is by supplying the information necessary to make consumers understand how they can gain points and rewards. Dunkin’ Donuts does this by letting users know they earn a free beverage reward with every 200 points earned; airlines do this by making each mile flown one mile earned for future redemption.
</p>

<p>
As technology has grown and expanded, so have the systems designed to reward consumers for their business. while scholars assert that the gamification of the consumer experience is, presently, harmful to consumers while benefiting companies, they also assert that these systems can be fixed in order to mutually benefit both consumers and businesses to create a positive game experience for all.
</p>


